  "digest": {
    "digest": "Diplomatic efforts to end the Iran war are intensifying, with Pakistani mediators actively involved in keeping peace talks alive. A potential war-ending proposal involves Iran relinquishing its uranium stockpile in exchange for the release of $20 billion in frozen US funds. President Trump indicated that a second round of talks could occur imminently, expressing optimism that the conflict should conclude soon, and even suggested a potential trip to Pakistan for a signing ceremony. The US has maintained pressure through a naval blockade of Iranian ports and sanctions on its oil industry, with military leaders stating readiness to strike Iranian infrastructure if ordered. European oil majors are reportedly benefiting from trading opportunities arising from the war, while global markets show a surprising sangfroid. The war's economic repercussions are felt globally, impacting trade fairs and driving up costs, though oil prices have seen fluctuations, notably falling when Iran declared the Strait of Hormuz open. Congressional attempts to curb presidential war powers have thus far failed in the House. Iran, meanwhile, has reiterated its stance on the Strait of Hormuz and its right to enrich uranium, though the level of enrichment is presented as negotiable.",
